    {
      "id": "53807e818189ac6c3dc28dfd9a98c6ede1acce1f",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2012-11-10 09:04:49.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\nI think it would be better to actually ignore unknown parameters, rather than having them prevent the system from mounting. Stopping the muh t has relatively little benefit, but there are definitely cases where an upgrade or mixed environment configuration could cause unknown parameters to be stored in the config.\n\nThis would also benefit from a test case that writes an invalid parameter into the config file using \"conf_param\" and then verified that a new mount does not fail.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "38cfb4855b68c022e44582bc98ba626a4ee9b79e",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 177,
        "name": "John Hammond",
        "email": "jhammond@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "jhammond"
      },
      "date": "2012-11-13 19:37:35.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nOK.\n\nWhat about invalid devices?\n\nlctl conf_param lustre-OST7fff.osc.max_dirty_mb=42\n\n(This causes client mount to fail.)",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
